The Merseyside giants found themselves facing a similar task on Thursday night after Dortmund scored twice in the opening nine minutes through Henrikh Mkhitaryan and Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang.
That put the visitors 3-1 up on aggregate after the first leg had ended 1-1.
"Very often in football the game is over then but not here, not with this Liverpool team," said former Dortmund boss Klopp.
Divock Origi, who scored in the first leg, reduced the deficit for the home side but the tie looked all but over when Marco Reus put the German side 3-1 up on the night and 4-2 ahead on aggregate.
